Over-Arching Goals

1) Analysis of premature births

A premature birth is defined as one that occurs before a gestational age of 270 days. We want to see the linear corilation between premature births from mothers that smoked durning their pregnancy vs.the mothers that did not smoke during their pregnancy.

2) Analysis of birth weights at gestational ages

To test the Surgeon Generals assertion that newborns of mothers who smoke have lower birth weights at every gestational age (number of days into the pregnancy when the child is born), we want to create graphs to visualize the linear relationship between smoking mothers and the babies weight at the gestational age.

Team Hypothesis

Question 1

We believe that there will be a strong positive corilation between premature births and mothers smoking while pregnant.

Question 2

There will be a positive correlation between the length of gestation and birth weight. Because the baby develops during gestation, it follows that a longer period of gestation would result in higher birth weight. We also predict that the children of smoking mothers will weigh less than children of non-smoking mothers.

Why Important

Question 1

Determining the effect smoking has on the rate of pre-term birth is of vital importance to new mothers. If smoking harms the health of a newborn child, the public must be informed of these risks so that they may take the necessary steps to protect themselves and their families.

Question 2

More Detailed Why Important

Question 1

If its found that smoking harms pregnant women and their babies, its reasonable to assume that expecting mothers would stop, or severely limit their smoking. This would deal a catastrophic blow to cigarette manufacturers. Additionally, it would provide further information as to why babies are born prematurely and could open up new avenues of inquiry as to the effects of smoking on pregnancy and birth.

Its imperative to note each of the variables taken into consideration during the experiment. While more variables result in less error, its nearly impossible to consider all of the threats. Note that the variables considered while running the numbers are as follows: ID, birthday, gestation length, birth weight, mothers/fathers race, mothers/fathers age, mothers/fathers education level, mothers/fathers pre-pregnancy weight, marital status of the mother, family income, mothers smoking, how long the mother has been smoking/ how long since she quit smoking, the number of cigarettes the mother smokes per-day, and if the baby was born prematurely.

Conclusion

The data proved our first hypothesis to be correct. It showed that full-term births were mainly attributed to non-smokers and that premature births were primarily ascribed to smokers. Whats more, the sample data was mainly made up of non-smokers and smokers. There werent many people reporting as in-between.

Plot for Hypothesis 2

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = gestation ~ bwtoz, data = babies)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        bwtoz  
##    238.2283       0.3422

Conclusion

We hypothesized that there would be a positive correlation between birth weight and gestation. After plotting and analyzing the data, we were proven correct. In our lm, the slope ( birth weight/gestation) is .3422 which indicates a positive correlation. Our secondary hypothesis concerning the effects of smoking on birth weight was slightly correct. We observed a weak negative correlation between birth weight and smoking. Our model showed that babies whose mothers smoke have a slightly lower birth weight than babies whose mothers do not. Lastly, the difference in color exhibited between premature and non-premature babies is interesting as it further demonstrates the correlation between gestation and birth weight.

Question

What is the correlation between a mothers pregnant weight and a babys birth weight? Do babies with mothers who smoke have a higher or lower birth weight? Are babies whose mothers smoke more likely to be premature than babies whose mothers dont smoke?

Hypothesis

I believe that there will be a positive correlation between birth weight and mothers pregnant weight. Additionally, I believe that Premature babies will have a lower birth weight than babies who are not premature. Lastly, I believe that in the premature section, there will be more babies whose mothers smoke than babies whose mothers did not smoke.

Birth Weight v. Mothers Weight in Relation to Smoking

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpregwt ~ bwtoz, data = babies)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        bwtoz  
##    104.2397       0.2044

Findings

I found that my hypothesis that there would be a positive correlation between a mothers pregnant weight and birth weight was correct. As shown by the lm slope, there is a weak positive correlation. Additionally, the plots show that there is a slight shift to the left in the premature graph as opposed to the not premature graph. This means that babies who are premature have a lower birth weight. Additionally, the data shows that there are more premature babies with mothers who smoked than with mothers who didnt smoke. This supports the two main questions because the plots show the relationship between a mothers weight, birth weight, premature, and smoking. Additionally, the data supports the two main questions because it shows that there is a negative correlation between premature and smoking, and a positive correlation between premature and smoking.
